messages.content: Behold, a new channel i thought of 🙂
Debate from a recent tweet I saw: are artists founders and are founders artists?
Neither. Entrepreneurs just want to be called anything but "Entrepreneur" because that term got ruined by dumbasses on youtube selling coaching lessons.
personally  💙  the interplay between art, design, science, + biz, etc. and entrepreneurship is probs more of a mindset. fndrs get this, so do artists

> Neither. Entrepreneurs just want to be called anything but "Entrepreneur" because that term got ruined by dumbasses on youtube selling coaching lessons.
@Prophet I want to screenshot and frame this statement
Isn’t that why “operator” became the new term lol
I’ve never heard anyone use the term “operator” before
I avoid the “What are you?” question
But if I’m forced to give an answer I go with founder
I actually really dislike the entrepreneur side of like
building things
we could make so much cooler, better things if everything wasn't based off finance
thats why I think people label it different things constantly (hackers, founders)
theres this desire to escape

> we could make so much cooler, better things if everything wasn't based off finance
@Prophet cooler yes definitely. But better is questionable, the reason finance exists is to show us if something is better than the alternatives, money is sort of the guage to how good our solutions are. Imo finance is as important as anything else, it's the language through which everyone distributes resources efficiently and calculates values for things. And when you think about its ability to coordinate vast numbers of people, it's quite amazing.
a fanged noumenon
@solderneer No i think thats such cap
I work in VC and it just isnt true
People prioritize exits and immediate profit, because they want their fund to return profitable margins every year so they can keep a fat check
Even the sequoias and FF of the world do that, because their priority is **investing** in great projects
There are endless things that could be built that would have infinite better impacts on the world if money wasnt a thing
Capitalism isnt some beautiful language. It just looks good because our entire society judges things by capitalistic values.
the bits of capitalism are human labor
stored in money
i don't see how you get a functioning society when you try to change that bit to beauty or anything else
no one will eat

Our society> Capitalism isnt some beautiful language. It just looks good because our entire society judges things by capitalistic values.
@Prophet  our society isn’t judged by capitalistic values, our society exists so that people can cooperate for survival, and the mechanism through which that happens is typically some exchange of goods and services. Money is just what happens when you generalise that concept for the convenience. So you can’t just remove money, if you really want to go down that road, you have to propose an alternative, else we are regressing back to a trade and barter system which is incredibly inefficient
Its something we've built cause its better than living in the stone age, sure. but its not a good thing, we should be trying to move past it asap.
My point was just for startups specifically, finances hold alot of people who are trying to build stuff back, and thats something sad

Ok but you see, let’s say I want to start a startup to make the world’s most expensive useless switch. It uses a Rube Goldberg processes to turn on a single light. Rightfully, no one else should fund this, it’s a waste of time (except me, I would fund myself because it’s fun). But without money, how do you tell if something is a waste of time. If there is no concept of value, anyone would be free to take resources and use it on any strange contraption they want. The investors have no way to check that this is the optimal solution to the problem, at best they can see that it solves a problem.
Money just provides a shortcut ofc, you don’t *only* consider money and how expensive something is.
But it’s a pretty straightforward shortcut and it’s quite indicative

If I was to provide an example, have you heard of solar roadways. On the surface it sounds like a brilliant idea, it actually got quite a bit of funding from various different countries’ governments.  But the instant you put it down to any scrutiny, the engineering challenges and just the simple physics barring the idea becomes quite obvious. And this was very simply reflected when you saw the ballooning costs of completing the project. This is just an example of how money effectively mirrors how good (or in this case bad) something is
@Prophet

@solderneer I like the hypotheticals but thats just now how startup funding works in anyway whatsoever. Also they straight up contradict some of the points you're trying to make (SolarRoadways got 2M under this system lol)
Not to like spam "go work in VC" but seriously go work in VC if you wanna test that hypothesis
When you are at a firm, you are looking for returns within your personal timeline, and more specifically projects that exit and that provide capitals
So that limits us dramatically
And its showing in todays world. Capitalist systems are easily the best system we have ever had as a society, but theyre unable to adapt to combat certain things

Ok but there are VCs that also invest in longer term “moonshot” ideas, for example I’ve worked with a VC called Mistletoe, which specifically invests in such longer term deep tech ideas.> When you are at a firm, you are looking for returns within your personal timeline, and more specifically projects that exit and that provide capitals
@Prophet
For Silicon valley? that means projects that dont provide exits, projects that dont provide capital returns get shafted. The issue is that those projects are **exactly what we desperately need**
There is no firm investing on like a 300 year basis.
Which is a timeline need for things like planetary colonization.
There aren't firms investing in things with altruistic value
If someone made a Useless fucking machine it doesnt take VC money to tell you that its useless lol
We should be worried about stuff thats restricting us
and right now, thats the financial system of the startup world.

Fair but I’d argue one wouldn’t invest directly in planetary colonisation. One would initially invest in technologies leading to it first. For example, mistletoe invested in a quantum encryption system with the foresight that in a quantum computer power world current encryption methods will become obsolete

I’m agreeable with maybe even 50/60 year timelines but 300 year timelines, an organisation that can really look that far would be super cool but also you have to come up with some way to manage that. Bear in mind 300 years ago we had no idea what was possible, we are notoriously bad at predicting the future

thats really not that long term thinking, quantum computing is reaching mainstream. Either way theyre doing that out of a desire to get a return, and they wouldnt do it if that return wasnt within their timeframe
Im not saying the entire ecosystem is broken. Alot of startup founders have short term goals, and they match up with VC goals of short term capital return
but there is a weakness in that system, which is showing in the lack of advancement we have had dealing with problems that arent capital based
How do you tell if your 300 year long moonshot is a shot in the dark or not? Also why would anyone give their capital up for this?
When they’d likely be dead
Exactly
You got it lmao
Oh no I get your point that these projects could possibly exist I’m just wondering how you would actually practically achieve it
The only way I can see this being achieved is through the state
Im not proposing a perfect solution, thats for sure
im just highlighting the issue

And your points are fair, like yea how the fuck am i gonna invest in stuff that far ahead in the future
but some of these projects are stuff we need to build
